I'm using hyprland on arch. want to be able to pull up information about my notes. I'm using alacritty and nvim. want it as a dropdown thing. suggestions?

Gemini said
Since you are on Arch with Hyprland, you have a couple of great ways to achieve a "Quake-style" dropdown (scratchpad) for your notes using Alacritty and Neovim.

The most efficient way to handle this in Hyprland is through Special Workspaces.

Option 1: The Native "Special Workspace" Way
This is the cleanest method because it doesn't require extra software. You define a "special" workspace that acts as a hidden layer, then create a rule to ensure your notes always open there.

Modify your hyprland.conf:
Add these lines to define the behavior and the keybind. Replace ~/notes with the path to your notes folder.

Bash
# Define the workspace behavior: when opened empty, launch Alacritty + Nvim
workspace = special:notes, on-created-empty:alacritty --class notes-floating -e nvim ~/notes

# Window rule to make it look like a dropdown
windowrulev2 = float, class:^(notes-floating)$
windowrulev2 = size 80% 70%, class:^(notes-floating)$
windowrulev2 = move center, class:^(notes-floating)$

# Keybind to toggle the dropdown (e.g., Super + N)
bind = $mainMod, N, togglespecialworkspace, notes
Option 2: Using Pyprland (Advanced & Smoother)
If you want actual "sliding" animations (like a real dropdown) and more control over "lost" windows, Pyprland is the community standard for scratchpads on Hyprland.

Install Pyprland:

Bash
sudo pacman -S pyprland  # Or via AUR if not in main repos
Create/Edit ~/.config/hypr/pyprland.toml:

Ini, TOML
[pyprland]
plugins = ["scratchpads"]

[scratchpads.notes]
animation = "fromTop"
command = "alacritty --class notes-dropterm -e nvim ~/notes"
class = "notes-dropterm"
size = "75% 60%"
lazy = true
Update hyprland.conf:

Bash
exec-once = pypr
bind = $mainMod, N, exec, pypr toggle notes
Pro-Tips for Your Note Workflow
Since you're using Neovim for notes, I highly recommend adding these to your init.lua or init.vim to make the "dropdown" experience feel more like a dedicated app:

Autosave: Use the plugin pocco81/auto-save.nvim so you never have to manually :w when closing the dropdown.

Telekasten / Obsidian.nvim: If you want a "Second Brain" feel, these plugins add fuzzy searching for notes, backlinking, and daily logs.

Conceal Level: Set vim.opt.conceallevel = 2 in your markdown config to hide syntax characters (like [[links]] or **bold**) for a cleaner look.

